# Stern-Brocot tree

## Definition

The **Stern-Brocot tree** is the complete binary tree whose nodes are
the positive rationals in lowest terms, generated by iterated
[mediant](mediant.md) from the boundary pair $(0/1,\, 1/0)$.  The
root is the mediant of the boundary pair, $(0 + 1)/(1 + 0) = 1/1$.
Each node $p/q$ has two children, the mediants of $p/q$ with its
left and right ancestors.

Every positive rational appears exactly once in the tree.

## Properties

- **Coprimality is automatic.**  If the parents of a node $(p/q)$ are
  Farey neighbors (i.e. $|ad - bc| = 1$), then so is $p/q$ with each
  of its parents.  Since the boundary pair $(0/1, 1/0)$ is a Farey
  pair, every node produced is in lowest terms.
- **Continued-fraction depth.**  The depth at which $p/q$ appears
  equals the sum of the partial quotients in its continued-fraction
  expansion, minus one.  Rationals near the golden section
  $1/\varphi$ appear at the greatest depth for a given denominator
  size.
- **Left-right paths encode continued fractions.**  The sequence of
  left-right moves from the root to $p/q$ encodes the continued
  fraction of $p/q$ in run-length form.

## Truncations

Cutting the tree at depth $N$ gives the **Stern-Brocot tree of depth
$N$**.  Its leaves are the rationals first appearing at depth $N$;
its boundary set is the [Farey sequence](farey_sequence.md)
$F_{N+1}$.  The [rational field equation](rational_field_equation.md)
is typically solved at a specific truncation depth.

## Role

The tree is the enumeration structure for mode-locking resonances:
every rotation-number plateau of the [circle map](circle_map.md)
corresponds to a unique tree node.  Every structural theorem about
the framework's integer ratios (Farey counts, Klein-bottle denominator
classes) reduces to a statement about a specific subtree.
